Name UI="D008819" MajorTopicYN="N">Mice, Nude</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D051379" MajorTopicYN="N">Mice</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D018450" MajorTopicYN="N">Disease Progression</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D002465" MajorTopicYN="N">Cell Movement</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008807" MajorTopicYN="N">Mice, Inbred BALB C</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D045744" MajorTopicYN="N">Cell Line, Tumor</DescriptorName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Ferroptosis</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Lung adenocarcinoma</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Targeted regulation</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">YBX1</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Declaration of competing interest The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>15</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="revised"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>7</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>8</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>27</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>54</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>14</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>39</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>13</Day><Hour>18</Hour><Minute>9</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>ppublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41389617</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/j.bbrc.2025.153109</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">S0006-291X(25)01825-X</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41371184</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>26</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1090-2104</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>795</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jan</Month><Day>08</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Biochemical and biophysical research communications</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Biochem Biophys Res Commun</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Observations on IL-2-inducible tyrosine kinase expression and Th17/Treg cell ratio in hyperoxia-induced bronchopulmonary dysplasia in neonatal rats.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>153076</StartPage><MedlinePgn>153076</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.bbrc.2025.153076</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0006-291X(25)01792-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The pathogenesis of bronchopulmonary dysplasia (BPD) is not fully understood, and there is currently a lack of effective therapeutic options. The immune responses of Th17 and Treg cells are regulated by the IL-2-inducible tyrosine kinase (ITK) signaling pathway, and the Th17/Treg imbalance is involved in the development of many lung diseases. However, the expression of Itk and the presence of a Th17/Treg imbalance in BPD have not been reported previously.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Neonatal Sprague-Dawley rats (&lt;12h old) were randomly assigned to hyperoxic (n&#xa0;=&#xa0;30) or air groups (n&#xa0;=&#xa0;30). At postnatal days (PD) 1,4,7,10,14, body weights were measured; 6 lungs/group were collected for H&amp;E staining, Itk mRNA (RT-qPCR) and protein (Western blot) assays. On PD14, 8 rats/group were evaluated for splenic Th17/Treg cell ratio (flow cytometry) and lung IL-17/IL-10 (ELISA).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Hyperoxic group showed lower weights at PD10-14 and reduced radial alveolar counts (PD4-14). Itk mRNA (PD4-14) and ITK protein (PD10-14) were downregulated. Splenic Th17&#xa0;cells and Th17/Treg ratio increased, while Tregs decreased. Lung IL-17 was higher and IL-10 lower in hyperoxic group.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Diminution in IL-2-inducible tyrosine kinase and Th17/Treg imbalance in hyperoxia-induced bronchopulmonary dysplasia model in neonatal rats, but the causal relationship between the two still needs to be confirmed by intervention studies.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025. Published by Elsevier Inc.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gong</LastName><ForeName>Xiaoxia</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Respiratory Medicine, Children's Hospital of Chongqing Medical University, National Clinical Research Center for Child Health and Disorders, Ministry of Education Key Laboratory of Child Development and Disorders, Chongqing Key Laboratory of Child Rare Diseases in Infection and Immunity, Chongqing, China; Anyue County People's Hospital, Ziyang, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Fu</LastName><ForeName>Xingmeng</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Respiratory Medicine, Children's Hospital of Chongqing Medical University, National Clinical Research Center for Child Health and Disorders, Ministry of Education Key Laboratory of Child Development and Disorders, Chongqing Key Laboratory of Child Rare Diseases in Infection and Immunity, Chongqi